\begin_layout Standard
Theoretically the problem of minimizing the average failure rate for two
 pure states has been solved in the previous section.
 However to be able to implement those schemes we resort to Neumark's theorem
 which states that any POVM operator can be realized by generalized measurements
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cite-keyneumark"

\end_inset

.
 The system where the incoming states live is embedded in a larger Hilbert
 space called ancilla.
 Then a unitary operator entangles the degrees of freedom of the system
 with those of the ancilla.
 After this interaction projective measurements are performed within this
 larger system in the ancilla.
 These measurements will also transform the system states in the original
 Hilbert space because of the entanglement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To show the power of Neumark's theorem we will re-derive the optimal failure
 rate of two nonorthogonal states.
 The incoming states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s},|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}\}$
\end_inset

 which live in the state Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{S}$
\end_inset

 are embedded with the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|i\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 which live in the ancilla Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{A}.$
\end_inset

 Now the system and the ancilla live in the larger Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H=H_{S}\varotimes H_{A}.$
\end_inset

 The incoming states in this larger Hilbert space can be written in the
 product form 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a},\ |\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a}\},$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket i_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the initial state of the ancilla.
 The unitary operator does the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a} & = & \sqrt{p_{1}}|\psi'_{1}\rangle_{s}|1\rangle_{a}+\sqrt{q_{1}}|\phi\rangle_{s}|0\rangle_{a},\nonumber \\
U|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a} & = & \sqrt{p_{2}}|\psi'_{2}\rangle_{s}|2\rangle_{a}+\sqrt{q_{2}}|\phi\rangle_{s}|0\rangle_{a},\label{eq:neumark}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of successfully identifying the state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle_{s}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of failing to identify 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle_{s},$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}+q_{i}=1.$
\end_inset

 The unitary operator aims to take the two incoming states and make them
 orthogonal.
 When there is a click on the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|1\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 the input states have been separated and output states 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi'_{i}\rangle_{s}$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal and therefore fully distinguishable.
 If there is a click along the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 the incoming states have been collapsed into a single state which carries
 no information about the system.
 That is why the choice on the setup of having the failed state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\phi\rangle_{s}$
\end_inset

 be the same, there should be absolutely no information left in the failed
 state, otherwise it is not optimal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the inner product of the two equations in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:neumark"

\end_inset

) gives the constraint to the optimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s=\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 was defined to be the overlap of the input states 
\begin_inset Formula $s\equiv\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 In just one line Neumark's setup has produced the constrain and the rest
 of the derivation, optimizing (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Q"

\end_inset

), is the same as in the POVM section and we do not need to repeat here.
 Implementation methods have been derived and we will show an example in
 Chapter 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Minimum Error Discrimination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Minimum Error (ME) strategy one is not allowed to abstain from identifyin
g an incoming state, i.e for every incoming state the observer must say which
 state he was given.
 Since it was shown that perfect discrimination is not possible the detectors
 inevitably will make errors.
 A click in a detector can only identify a state with some probability of
 success and misidentify the state with some probability of error.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Minimum Error: Two mixed states via POVM 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given an ensemble of two mixed states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\rho_{1},\rho_{2}\}$
\end_inset

 prepared with different a priori probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\eta_{1},\eta_{2}\}$
\end_inset

 the task is to minimize the rate for which the detectors misidentify a
 state.
 The minimum error problem for two pure or mixed states was first solved
 by Helstrom 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Helstrom1969"

\end_inset

.
 We show an alternative derivation to ME of two pure states developed by
 Herzog 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Herzog2004"

\end_inset

 and Fuchs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fuchs1996"

\end_inset

.
 When the detector 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 clicks for state 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{j}$
\end_inset

 it is an error, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}=Tr(\rho_{j}\Pi_{i})$
\end_inset

, a clink for state 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

 is success 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=Tr(\rho_{i}\Pi_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus for two states we want to minimize the following expression.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\eta_{1}Tr(\rho_{1}\Pi_{2})+\eta_{2}Tr(\rho_{2}\Pi_{1}).\label{eq:P_E}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}+\Pi_{2}=I$
\end_inset

, Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:P_E"

\end_inset

) can be rewritten as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{E} & = & \eta_{1}Tr(\rho_{1}(I-\Pi_{1}))+\eta_{2}Tr(\rho_{2}\Pi_{1}),\\
 & = & \eta_{1}+Tr[(\eta_{2}\rho_{2}-\eta_{1}\rho_{1})\Pi_{1},\\
 & = & \eta_{2}-Tr[(\eta_{2}\rho_{2}-\eta_{1}\rho_{1})\Pi_{2}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda=\eta_{2}\rho_{2}-\eta_{1}\rho_{1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\eta_{1}+Tr(\Lambda\Pi_{1})=\eta_{2}-Tr(\Lambda\Pi_{2}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To minimize 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 should project onto the eigenvectors of the negative eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda,$
\end_inset

 on the other hand 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{2}$
\end_inset

 should project onto the positive eigenvectors.
 Let us write 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 into its spectral decomposition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Lambda=\eta_{2}\rho_{2}-\eta_{1}\rho_{1}=\sum_{i=1}^{d}\lambda_{i}|\lambda_{i}\rangle\langle\lambda_{i}|.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To implement the projection of the POVM operators onto the positive (or
 negative) eigenvectors the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 can be split into three categories without any loss of generality: negative,
 positive and zero:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\lambda_{i} & < & 0\text{ for }1\leq i<i_{o},\nonumber \\
\lambda_{i} & > & 0\text{ for \ensuremath{i_{o}\leq i<d}},\nonumber \\
\lambda_{i} & = & 0\text{ for \ensuremath{d\leq i<d_{s}}. }
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then from the spectral decomposition we can rewrite 
\begin_inset Formula $(2.2.6)$
\end_inset

 in terms of the optimal POVM.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\eta_{1}+\sum_{i=1}^{i_{o}-1}\lambda_{i}\langle\lambda_{i}|\Pi_{1}|\lambda_{i}\rangle=\eta_{2}-\sum_{i=i_{o}}^{d_{s}}\lambda_{i}\langle\lambda_{i}|\Pi_{2}|\lambda_{i}\rangle,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}=\sum_{i=1}^{i_{o}-1}\lambda_{i}|\lambda_{i}\rangle\langle\lambda_{i}|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{2}=\sum_{i=i_{o}}^{d_{s}}\lambda_{i}|\lambda_{i}\rangle\langle\lambda_{i}|.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The POVMs need to satisfy the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\langle\lambda_{i}|\Pi_{j}|\lambda_{i}\rangle\leq1$
\end_inset

 which comes from the definition of the normalized probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}=Tr(\rho_{i}\Pi_{j}).$
\end_inset

 These POVMs are basically von Neumann projectors onto the corresponding
 eigenvectors.
 If we now replace the detection operators by the optimal detectors the
 minimum error can be expressed just in terms of the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{E} & = & \eta_{1}-\sum_{i=1}^{i_{o}-1}|\lambda_{i}|=\eta_{2}-\sum_{i=1}^{d_{s}}|\lambda_{i}|,\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}[1-\sum_{i=1}^{d_{s}}|\lambda_{i}|]=\frac{1}{2}[1-Tr|\Lambda|],\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}[1-Tr|\eta_{2}\rho_{2}-\eta_{1}\rho_{1}|]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the states to be discriminated are pure, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,|\psi_{2}\rangle\},$
\end_inset

 the minimum error can be reduced to 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\frac{1}{2}[1-\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{2}}].
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

