\begin_layout Subsection
Minimum Error: Two pure states via Neumark's theorem 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just as we did in the UD case, we will solve the ME problem of discriminating
 two pure states via the Neumark setup because of it lends itself into an
 optical implementation.
 Although in this case the solution is not as straightforward.
 The incoming states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s},|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}\}$
\end_inset

 which live in the state Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{S}$
\end_inset

 are embedded with the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|i\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 which live in the ancilla Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{A}.$
\end_inset

 Now the system and the ancilla live in the larger Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H=H_{S}\varotimes H_{A}.$
\end_inset

 The incoming states in this larger Hilbert space can be written in the
 product form 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a},\ |\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a}\}.$
\end_inset

 The unitary operator does the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a} & = & \sqrt{p_{1}}|\psi_{1}\rangle|1\rangle+\sqrt{r_{1}}|\psi_{2}\rangle|2\rangle,\\
U|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}|i\rangle_{a} & = & \sqrt{p_{2}}|\psi_{2}\rangle|2\rangle+\sqrt{r_{2}}|\psi_{1}\rangle|1\rangle,\label{eq:ME neumark}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of having successfully identified the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{i}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of misidentifying the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{j}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the inner product of the two equations in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ME neumark"

\end_inset

) gives the constraint:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s=\sqrt{p_{1}r_{2}}+\sqrt{p_{2}r_{1}}.\label{eq:ME constraint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The quantity we are looking to minimize in the average error rate:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2},\label{eq:ME}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 subject to the constraint in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ME constraint"

\end_inset

).
 Adding the constraint to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ME"

\end_inset

 with one Lagrange multiplier and using 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}+r_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{E}=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}+\lambda\left[s-\sqrt{(1-r_{1})r_{2}}-\sqrt{(1-r_{2})r_{1}}\right].
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Differentiating with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

, then setting the resulting equations equal to zero yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial F_{E}}{\partial r_{1}}=\eta_{1}+\frac{1}{2}\left[\sqrt{\frac{r_{2}}{1-r_{1}}}-\sqrt{\frac{1-r_{2}}{r_{1}}}\right]=0,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial F_{E}}{\partial r_{2}}=\eta_{2}+\frac{1}{2}\left[-\sqrt{\frac{r_{1}}{1-r_{2}}}+\sqrt{\frac{1-r_{1}}{r_{2}}}\right]=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rearranging the above two equations so that the left hand side is only a
 function of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the right hand sides turn out to be equivalent, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{2\eta_{1}}{\lambda}\sqrt{r_{1}(1-r_{1})}=\sqrt{r_{1}r_{2}}-\sqrt{(1-r_{1})(1-r_{2})},\label{eq:r12}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{2\eta_{2}}{\lambda}\sqrt{r_{2}(1-r_{2})}=\sqrt{r_{1}r_{2}}-\sqrt{(1-r_{1})(1-r_{2})}.\label{eq:r1r2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The right hand sides of Eq.(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r12"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r1r2"

\end_inset

) can be set to a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2\eta_{i}}{\lambda}\sqrt{r_{i}(1-r_{i})}\equiv C$
\end_inset

, which can later be determined from the unitarity constraint 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ME constraint"

\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r_{i} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left(1\pm\sqrt{1-\frac{\lambda^{2}C^{2}}{\eta_{i}^{2}}}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(1-\sqrt{1-\frac{\delta^{2}}{\eta_{i}^{2}}}\right),\label{eq:r_i-1}\\
r_{i} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1-A_{i}\right],
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}\equiv\sqrt{1-\frac{\delta^{2}}{\eta_{i}^{2}}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{2}\equiv\lambda^{2}C^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The smaller 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is picked (lower sign in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r_i-1"

\end_inset

 ) as this represents error rate, which is to be minimized.
 Now replace 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 into the constraint (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ME constraint"

\end_inset

) and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
s & = & \sqrt{(1-r_{1})r_{2}}+\sqrt{(1-r_{2})r_{1}},\\
2s & = & \sqrt{(1+A_{1})(1-A_{2})}+\sqrt{(1-A_{1})(1+A_{2})},\\
2s^{2} & = & 1-A_{1}A_{2}+\sqrt{(1-A_{1}^{2})(1-A_{2}^{2})},\\
2s^{2} & = & 1-A_{1}A_{2}+\frac{\delta^{2}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}},\\
(2s^{2}-1 & -\frac{\delta^{2}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}})^{2}= & 1-\frac{\delta^{2}}{\eta_{1}^{2}}-\frac{\delta^{2}}{\eta_{2}^{2}}+\frac{\delta^{4}}{\eta_{1}^{2}\eta_{2}^{2}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After some tedious but trivial algebra:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta^{2}=\frac{4s^{2}(1-s^{2})\eta_{1}^{2}\eta_{2}^{2}}{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}.\label{eq:delta}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now substitute the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:delta"

\end_inset

) into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r_i-1"

\end_inset

) to get the explicit form of the individual error rates,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
r_{i}=\frac{1}{2}\left[1-\frac{1-2\eta_{i}s^{2}}{\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inserting 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:P_E"

\end_inset

) Helstrom bound is retrieved 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Helstrom1969"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{E} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1-\frac{\eta_{1}-2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}{\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}}-\frac{\eta_{2}-2\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}{\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}}\right],\nonumber \\
P_{E} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1-\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}\right].
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we mentioned above the advantage of solving the ME problem via Neumark
 is that we now have explicit expressions for the individual error rates,
 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}.$
\end_inset

 In the Implementation chapter, it is shown that the unitary operator which
 carries out this operation can be written in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and then be decomposed into beam splitters and phase shifters using optical
 interferometers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Optimal discrimination of a certain class of mixed states with a fixed rate
 of inconclusive outcome (FRIO)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter we will derive the optimal strategy with a Fixed Rate of
 Inconclusive Outcomes (
\begin_inset Formula $FRIO$
\end_inset

) that optimally interpolates between the two well known limits, Helstrom
 bound for minimum error and IDP for unambiguous discrimination.
 In particular, as the main finding of our paper, we will show that the
 optimal distribution of the fixed rate of inconclusive outcomes, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, among the 2-dimensional subspaces spanned by the pair of Jordan basis
 vectors is highly non-trivial and an interesting threshold-like structure
 emerges: As we start increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0$
\end_inset

 , first only one subspace receives the entire inconclusive rate.
 Then, as we increase 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 further, at a certain threshold a second subspace starts sharing the inconclusi
ve rate.
 If we increase 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 further, at another threshold a third subspace also starts sharing 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 , and so on, until above a last threshold all subspaces share the available
 inconclusive rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Review of the FRIO solution for two pure states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first present a brief review of the method developed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bagan2012"

\end_inset

 for the two pure state optimal FRIO problem since the rest of the paper
 relies heavily on this method.
 We derive the maximum probability of success or, equivalently, the minimum
 probability of error in identifying the states, when a certain fixed rate
 of inconclusive outcomes is allowed.
 By varying the inconclusive rate, the scheme optimally interpolates between
 Unambiguous and Minimum Error discrimination (UD and ME).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In all of these scenarios (UD, ME or FRIO) one is given a system which is
 promised to be prepared in one of two known pure states, 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, but we don't know which.
 The pure states are prepared with prior probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

, respectively, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 It is well known that two pure states can be discriminated both unambiguously
 and with minimum error.
 In Section (2.1) we showed the solution of the optimal average inconclusive
 rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 for UD:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{{\rm c}}=\left\{ \begin{array}{l}
\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}\cos^{2}\theta,\mbox{if \ensuremath{{\displaystyle \eta_{1}<\frac{\cos^{2}\theta}{1+\cos^{2}\theta}\equiv\eta_{1}^{(l)}}},}\\[0.7em]
\eta_{2}+\eta_{1}\cos^{2}\theta,\mbox{if \ensuremath{\eta_{1}>{\displaystyle \frac{1}{1+\cos^{2}\theta}\equiv\eta_{1}^{(r)}}},}\\[0.7em]
2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}\cos\theta\equiv Q_{0},\mbox{if \ensuremath{\eta_{1}^{(l)}\le\eta_{1}\le\eta_{1}^{(r)}}}\ ,
\end{array}\right.\label{Qmax}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|\equiv\cos\theta$
\end_inset

 is the overlap of the input states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Section (2.2) we also showed the optimal average error rate for ME: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{{\rm E}}^{ME}=\frac{1}{2}\left(1-\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\cos^{2}\theta}\;\right).\label{PE}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It has long been suggested 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chefles1998"

\end_inset

 that the above state discrimination points are part of a more general scheme.
 One which interpolates between optimal ME and UD.
 The FRIO strategy achieves that goal by minimizing the error rate while
 allowing for some rate of inconclusive results.
 Hence the strategy has three measurement outcomes, one that identifies
 with the first state, one that identifies with the second state and one
 that does not identify with a state at all, corresponding to the inconclusive
 outcome.
 The authors in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bagan2012"

\end_inset

 solve the problem via the POVM method.
 Three POVM elements are needed such that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{1}+\Pi_{2}+\Pi_{0}=I\ ,\label{POVM}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A click in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is identified with state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}},$
\end_inset

 a click in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is identified with the second state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

 and any clicks in the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to inconclusive outcomes.
 However the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 can also click for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{j}}.$
\end_inset

 We wish to minimize the average error rate,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{E} & = & \eta_{1}Tr\left[\sandwich{\psi_{1}}{\Pi_{2}}{\psi_{1}}\right]+\eta_{2}Tr\left[\sandwich{\psi_{2}}{\Pi_{1}}{\psi_{2}}\right],\\
 & = & \eta_{1}tr\left[\Pi_{2}\ket{\psi_{1}}\bra{\psi_{1}}\right]+\eta_{2}tr\left[\Pi_{1}\ket{\psi_{2}}\bra{\psi_{2}}\right],\\
 & = & \eta_{1}tr\left[\Pi_{2}\rho_{1}\right]+\eta_{2}tr\left[\Pi_{1}\rho_{2}\right],
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}=\ket{\psi_{1}}\bra{\psi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{2}=\ket{\psi_{2}}\bra{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

 are the corresponding pure state density matrices (Equivalently we wish
 to maximize the average success rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}=\eta_{1}tr\left[\Pi_{1}\rho_{1}\right]+\eta_{2}tr\left[\Pi_{2}\rho_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

), for a fixed rate of inconclusive results,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q=\eta_{1}tr\left[\Pi_{0}\rho_{1}\right]+\eta_{2}tr\left[\Pi_{0}\rho_{2}\right]\ .\label{Q}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution to the problem involves a neat trick which transforms the three
 element POVM defined in Eq.(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "POVM"

\end_inset

) into a two element POVM, namely,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Pi_{1}+\Pi_{2} & = & I-\Pi_{0},\nonumber \\
\Omega^{-1/2}\left(\Pi_{1}+\Pi_{2}\right)\Omega^{-1/2} & = & \Omega^{-1/2}\left(I-\Pi_{0}\right)\Omega^{-1/2},\nonumber \\
\tilde{\Pi}_{1}+\tilde{\Pi}_{2} & = & I,
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\equiv I-\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Pi}_{i}\equiv\Omega^{-1/2}\Pi_{i}\,\Omega^{-1/2}.$
\end_inset

 Should be noted that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{-1/2}=\left(I-\Pi_{0}\right)^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

 exists unless 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 has a unit value, in which case the problem is treated separately.
 It was important to notice that for optimal FRIO, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 must be rank one operator.
 That means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 maps both incoming non-orthogonal states onto a single state which is then
 discarded.
 On the other hand the other two POVM elements map the input states onto
 two different states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The FRIO problem has essentially been transformed into a new parametrized
 optimization scheme with two POVM elements, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Pi}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Pi}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The error probability in the new parametrized form, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=(1-Q)\tilde{P}_{E}$
\end_inset

, becomes 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\tilde{P}_{e} & = & Tr(\tilde{\eta}_{1}\tilde{\rho}_{1}\tilde{\Pi}_{2})+Tr(\tilde{\eta}_{2}\tilde{\rho}_{2}\tilde{\Pi}_{1}),\label{tildePe}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the normalized states 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\rho}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and normalized a priori probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\eta}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\rho}_{i}=\frac{\Omega^{1/2}\rho_{i}\Omega^{1/2}}{Tr(\Omega\rho_{i}))},\qquad\tilde{\eta}_{i}=\frac{\eta_{i}Tr(\Omega\rho_{i})}{1-Q},\label{tildestates}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "tildePe"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Pi}_{1}+\tilde{\Pi}_{2}=I$
\end_inset

