\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:separation constraint"

\end_inset

) and no further optimization is necessary:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
s & = & ps'+q,\nonumber \\
p & = & \frac{1-s}{1-s'}.\label{eq:separation-1}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will now show applications of state separation to exact cloning and unambiguo
us state discrimination.
 Another application to state separation for equal priors is in hybrid cloning,
 see Section (3.6.1).
 Let us begin by showing the connection to exact cloning with failure rate.
 Suppose we are given a quantum system in either of the pure states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}},\ket{\psi_{2}}\right\} $
\end_inset

, such that the two states are non-orthogonal.
 The task is to produce two perfect copies of the input state.
 Let us embed the quantum system with a blank state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket i$
\end_inset

 so the system becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}}\ket i,\ket{\psi_{2}}\ket i\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 A perfect copying machine should produce 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}}\ket{\psi_{1}},\ket{\psi_{2}}\ket{\psi_{2}}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 A modified Neumark setup from state separation in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:separation"

\end_inset

) for cloning is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p}\ket{\psi_{1}}\ket{\psi_{1}}\ket{\alpha}+\sqrt{q}|\Phi_{o}\rangle|f\rangle,\nonumber \\
U|\psi_{2}\rangle|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p}\ket{\psi_{1}}\ket{\psi_{1}}\ket{\alpha}+\sqrt{q}|\Phi_{o}\rangle|f\rangle,\label{eq:cloning}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inner product gives the unitarity constraint which is enough to fully
 solve the problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
s & = & ps^{2}+q\nonumber \\
p & = & \frac{1-s}{1-s^{2}}=\frac{1}{1+s}\label{eq:cloning-1}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We notice that the success probability of producing two perfect clones with
 a rate of abstention (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cloning-1"

\end_inset

) could be derived from state separation success rate in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:separation-1"

\end_inset

) by replacing the overlap of output states 
\begin_inset Formula $s'$
\end_inset

 with the square overlap of input states 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that the Duan-Guo limit 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Duan1998"

\end_inset

 is a special case of state separation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally, state separation can be modified to produce 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 copies of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}},\ket{\psi_{2}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 initial copies, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N\geq M$
\end_inset

.
 We derived the solution of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 cloning in section (3.2.1).
 It could simply be derived from Eq.
