This is the relationship that gives the optimal clones and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 should be replaced in 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{MN}$
\end_inset

.
 To be able to use this relationship we re-express 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{MN}$
\end_inset

 in a different way: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\eta_{1}\cos2(\alpha-x)+\eta_{2}\cos2(\alpha+x)\right],\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[\cos2\alpha\cos2x\left\{ 1+(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})\tan2\alpha\tan2x\right\} \right]+\frac{1}{2},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 we can rewrite (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:tan2x"

\end_inset

) as 
\begin_inset Formula $(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})\tan2\alpha=\frac{\sin2x}{\cos2x}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\thinspace\cos2x=\frac{\sqrt{1-\cos^{2}2x}}{(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})\tan2\alpha}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2})^{2}\tan^{2}(2\alpha)}}.$
\end_inset

 Finally the optimal fidelity can be expressed in terms of the a-priori
 probabilities and the overlap of the input states only .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\cos2\alpha\cos2x\left\{ 1+\left(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2}\right)\tan2\alpha\tan2x\right\} \right],\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\frac{\cos2\alpha}{\sqrt{1+\left(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2}\right)^{2}\tan^{2}(2\alpha)}}\{1+\left(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2}\right)^{2}\tan^{2}2\alpha\right],\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\cos2\alpha\sqrt{1+\left(\eta_{1}-\eta_{2}\right)^{2}\tan^{2}2\alpha}\right],\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\sqrt{\cos^{2}2\alpha+\left(1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\right)\sin^{2}2\alpha}\right],\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\sin^{2}2\alpha}\right],\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\sin^{2}\left(2\theta-\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)\right)}\right].\label{eq:fid}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the asymptotic limit, producing infinitely many copies 
\begin_inset Formula $N\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, fidelity merges into the Helstrom bound in the discrimination of non-orthogona
l pure states.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos2\theta=s^{M}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2})=s^{N}$
\end_inset

 and expanding the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin$
\end_inset

 term under the square root, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sin\left(2\theta-\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)\right) & = & \sin2\theta\cos\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)-\cos2\theta\sin\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)\\
 & = & \sqrt{1-\cos^{2}(2\theta)}\cos\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)-\cos2\theta\sin\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)\\
 & = & \sqrt{1-s^{2M}}s^{N}-s^{M}\sqrt{1-s^{2N}}\\
 & = & -s^{M}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting back into Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fid"

\end_inset

) Helstrom bound emerges: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{Mâ}=\frac{1}{2}[1+\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\cos^{2}(2\theta)}]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the mathematics shows the convergence of Fidelity into optimal minimum
 error state discrimination it is not clear as to why this connection should
 exist at all.
 On the one hand fidelity optimizes the average overlap between the clones
 and input states while ME state discrimination minimizes the error rate
 of failing to distinguish the incoming state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will show the connection in the following two step process: first measure
 and prepare then optimize the fidelity rate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Step 1: Measure and prepare
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Discriminate the incoming states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}^{M}},\ket{\psi_{2}^{M}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 with optimal ME then prepare states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}^{N}},\ket{\psi_{2}^{N}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 with the corresponding probabilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}^{M}\rangle|0\rangle & = & \sqrt{p_{1}}|\psi_{1}^{N}\rangle|1\rangle+\sqrt{r_{1}}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|2\rangle,\\
U|\psi_{2}^{M}\rangle|0\rangle & = & \sqrt{r_{2}}|\psi_{1}^{N}\rangle|1\rangle+\sqrt{p_{2}}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|2\rangle,
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{i}^{M}}$
\end_inset

 is received we successfully prepare the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{i}^{N}}$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 and mistakenly prepare the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{j}^{N}}$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Step 2: Optimize the fidelity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The global fidelity for state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}^{N}}$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F_{1} & = & p_{1}|\braket{\psi_{1}}{\psi_{1}}|^{N}+r_{1}|\braket{\psi_{2}}{\psi_{1}}|^{2N},\\
 & = & p_{1}+r_{1}|\braket{\psi_{2}}{\psi_{1}}|^{2N}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly for state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}^{N}}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{2}=p_{2}+r_{2}|\braket{\psi_{1}}{\psi_{2}}|^{2N}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The average fidelity for both states is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{MN} & = & \eta_{1}F_{1}+\eta_{2}F_{2}\nonumber \\
 & = & \eta_{1}\left(p_{1}+r_{1}|\braket{\psi_{2}}{\psi_{1}}|^{2N}\right)+\eta_{2}\left(p_{2}+r_{2}|\braket{\psi_{1}}{\psi_{2}}|^{2N}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \eta_{1}p_{1}+\eta_{2}p_{2}+\eta_{1}r_{1}s^{2N}+\eta_{2}r_{2}s^{2N}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is now clear that in the asymptotic limit 
\begin_inset Formula $N\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 fidelity reproduces the Helstrom bound 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{MN}=\eta_{1}p_{1}+\eta_{2}p_{2}.$
\end_inset

 However the relationship between optimal fidelity and optimal state discriminat
ion for a finite number of copies 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 remains an open question.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hybrid Cloning: Interpolation between exact and approximate cloning 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we seek to interpolate between probabilistic exact cloning
 and approximate cloning machines using our results from state separation.
 Exact cloning machines produce perfect clones while allowing for some inconclus
ive outcomes.
 Approximate cloning machines produce copies on demand which resemble the
 input states by maximizing the fidelity.
 One can imagine a scheme where fidelity can be higher then maximum fidelity
 in the approximate cloning machine while it allows for a fixed rate of
 inconclusive outcomes, FRIO.
 This scheme should reproduce exact cloning and approximate cloning machines
 by setting FRIO to 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}$
\end_inset

 and zero respectively.
 Chefles and Barnett 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chefles1999"

\end_inset

 solved the problem for the case when the input states are prepared with
 equal a priori probabilities.
 We extend the solution to the more general case when the states are prepared
 with different priors.
 Such a solution is possible due to our recent work on making 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 perfect clones from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 copies of one of two known pure states with minimum failure probability
 in the general case where the known states have arbitrary priori probabilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equal priors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution to the interpolation of cloning for equal a priori probabilities
 has been derived by Chefles et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chefles1999"

\end_inset

.
 The authors develop a scheme which, depending on the fidelity of the clones,
 can interpolate between exact cloning with inconclusive results in one
 extreme and optimal approximate cloning on the other extreme.
 In our work this scheme has been generalized for the case when the input
 states are prepared with different a priori probabilities.
 First we show the derivation of the equal priors as it will help to better
 understand the general case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{2}=1/2,$
\end_inset

 the output states are symmetric, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}=\phi_{2}=\phi,$
\end_inset

 and the optimal global fidelity, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{MN}$
\end_inset

, in Eq.(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fid"

\end_inset

) reduces to: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\sqrt{1-\sin^{2}\left(2\theta-2\phi\right)}\right],\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\cos^{2}\left(2\theta-2\phi\right)\right].\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Duan and Guo 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Duan1998"

\end_inset

 showed that the maximum success probability of obtaining 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 exact clones from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 given copies of non-orthogonal quantum states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,|\psi_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

, which are prepared with equal a priori probabilities, is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{MN}=\frac{1-s^{M}}{1-s^{N}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is the overlap of the input states 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 The success rate for 1 to 2 cloning, 
\begin_inset Formula $M=1,N=2,$
\end_inset

 reduces to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{12}=\frac{1}{1+s}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The interpolation takes us from optimal exact cloning to maximum fidelity.
 Given a set 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 of two non-orthogonal quantum states, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\psi_{1}\rangle,|\psi_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 the goal is to make 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 clones 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|\phi_{1}\rangle,|\phi_{2}\rangle\}$
\end_inset

, which are similar to the input states but not perfect.
 The Neumark setup is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle^{\otimes M}|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p}|\phi_{1}\rangle^{\oplus N}|1\rangle+\sqrt{q}|f\rangle|0\rangle\label{eq:NeumarkClone1}\\
U|\psi_{2}\rangle^{\oplus M}|i\rangle & = & \sqrt{p}|\phi_{2}\rangle^{\oplus N}|1\rangle+\sqrt{q}|f\rangle|0\rangle\label{eq:NeumarkClone2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The input states are prepared with equal a priori probabilities.
 A click in the 
\begin_inset Formula $|1\rangle$
\end_inset

 direction means that we succeed in making the clones and the probability
 of success is 
\begin_inset Formula $p.$
\end_inset

 A click in the 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle$
\end_inset

 direction means that we failed to create a clone with a probability 
\begin_inset Formula $q.$
\end_inset

 The inner product or (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NeumarkClone1"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NeumarkClone2"

\end_inset

) gives the constraint: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s^{M}=ps'^{N}+q
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the unitarity condition 
\begin_inset Formula $p+q=1,$
\end_inset

 the average rate of successfully making a clone is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p=\frac{1-s^{M}}{1-s'^{N}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $s'$
\end_inset

 is the overlap of the clones 
\begin_inset Formula $s'=\langle\phi_{1}|\phi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 If the final states are orthogonal, 
\begin_inset Formula $s'=0$
\end_inset

 then the state separation reaches the IDP limit and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{S}=P_{IDP}=1-|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{M}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we express the overlap of the output states in terms on the success
 rates and the overlap of input states,
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos2\theta=|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{N}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
|\langle\phi_{1}|\phi_{2}\rangle|^{N} & = & 1-\frac{1-|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{M}}{P_{S}}\\
\cos^{N}(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}) & = & 1-\frac{P_{IDP}}{P_{S}}\label{eq:seperation}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The exact clones live in an N dimensional space 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1,2}^{N}\rangle=\cos\theta|1\rangle\pm\sin\theta|0\rangle.$
\end_inset

 The approximate clones can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $|\phi_{1,2}\rangle=\cos\phi_{1}|1\rangle\pm\sin\phi_{1}|0\rangle$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fidelity rate for equal priors is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{MN}=\frac{1}{2}\left[1+\cos(2\theta-\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and we want to use the relationship in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:seperation"

\end_inset

).
 Let us expand the cosine term 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(2\theta-\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)\right)=\cos2\theta\cos\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)+\sin2\theta\sin\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fidelity becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\\
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+|\langle\psi_{1}^{N}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|\left(1-\frac{P_{IDP}}{P_{S}}\right)+\frac{1}{P_{S}}(\left(1-|\langle\psi_{1}^{N}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|^{2}\right)\left(P_{S}^{2}-\left(P_{S}-P_{IDP}\right)^{2}\right)^{1/2}\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 As 
\begin_inset Formula $N\rightarrow\infty,\thinspace|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{N}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{MN}$
\end_inset

 reduces to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{MN}=\frac{1}{2}[1+\frac{1}{P_{S}}\sqrt{P_{S}^{2}-(P_{S}-P_{IDP})^{2}}].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also express the fidelity in terms of fixed failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=1-P_{S}$
\end_inset

 which serves as the parameter by which we are interpolating and the optimal
 failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}=\left|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle\right|$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+|\langle\psi_{1}^{N}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|(1-\frac{1-Q_{o}}{1-Q})+\frac{1}{1-Q}(\left(1-|\langle\psi_{1}^{N}|\psi_{2}^{N}\rangle|^{2}\right)\left(\left(1-Q\right)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}\right)^{1/2}\right],\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2\left(1-Q\right)}\left[(1-Q)+Q_{o}^{N}(Q_{o}-Q)+\sqrt{(1-Q_{o}^{2N})\left[(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}\right]}\right].
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

In the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $N\rightarrow\infty,\thinspace|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|^{N}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\frac{1}{1-Q}\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}\right],\\
(1-Q)F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[(1-Q)+\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}\right].
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(1-Q)F_{MN}=P_{succes}$
\end_inset

, the probability of successfully identifying a state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{success} & = & \frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)+\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(This is a different success rate then the 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{S}$
\end_inset

 defined above, the 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{S}$
\end_inset

 was defined as the rate of successfully carrying out a state separation.
 )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This formula describes the relationship between the discrimination of states
 with a fixed rate of inconclusive outcome.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0$
\end_inset

 it reaches the Helstrom bound of minimum error and when 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{o}$
\end_inset

 it reaches the IDP limit in UD.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
General case
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We would like to generalize the above results for the case when the incoming
 states are prepared with different prior probabilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Step 1: State Separation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Optimally separate the incoming states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}^{M}},\ket{\psi_{2}^{M}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 with a fixed rate of inconclusive results 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

, then prepare states 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\psi_{1}^{N}},\ket{\psi_{2}^{N}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 with the corresponding success probabilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|\psi_{1}^{M}\rangle|0\rangle & = & \sqrt{p_{1}}|\phi_{1}\rangle|1\rangle+\sqrt{q_{1}}|\Phi\rangle|2\rangle,\nonumber \\
U|\psi_{2}^{M}\rangle|0\rangle & = & \sqrt{p_{2}}|\phi_{2}\rangle|1\rangle+\sqrt{q_{2}}|\Phi\rangle|2\rangle,
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The incoming states are separated with a success probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 and failed to separate the states with a failure probability 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The inner product of the two equations gives the unitarity constraint
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s=\sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}s'+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\label{eq:setaration constraint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Step 2: Optimize Fidelity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fidelity for state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 is: 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}=\left|\braket{\psi_{1}^{N}}{\phi_{1}}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly the fidelity for state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\braket{\psi_{2}^{N}}{\phi_{2}}\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The overall fidelity is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=\frac{\eta_{1}p_{1}F_{1}+\eta_{2}p_{2}F_{2}}{\eta_{1}p_{1}+\eta_{2}p_{2}}=\frac{\eta_{1}p_{1}F_{1}+\eta_{2}p_{2}F_{2}}{1-Q}=\tilde{\eta}_{1}F_{1}+\tilde{\eta}_{2}F_{2},
\]

\end_inset

where the normalized a priori probabilities are 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\eta}_{i}=\frac{\eta_{i}p_{i}}{1-Q}$
\end_inset

.
 The average fidelity is the same as calculated in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fid"

\end_inset

) with the new normalized probabilities: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{MN} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1+\sqrt{1-4\tilde{\eta}_{1}\tilde{\eta}_{2}\sin^{2}\left(2\theta-\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)\right)}\right],\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2(1-Q)}\left[(1-Q)+\sqrt{\left(1-Q\right)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}p_{1}p_{2}\sin^{2}\left(2\theta-\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)\right)}\right],
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be seen that in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $N\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, expanding the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin$
\end_inset

 term as we did in the previous section, the FRIO 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bagan2012"

\end_inset

 results are recovered.
 It again shows a close relationship between fidelity and state discrimination.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving the problem of hybrid cloning however requires one last optimization,
 that of the second term under the square root
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Lambda & = & \sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}\sin\left(2\theta-\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)\right),\\
 & = & \sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}\sqrt{1-s^{2n}}s'-\sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}(1-s'^{2}})s^{n}\\
 & = & \sqrt{1-s^{2n}}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)-s^{n}\sqrt{1-(q_{1}+q_{2})+q_{1}q_{2}-\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}},\\
 & = & \sqrt{1-s^{2n}}\left(s-u\right)-s^{n}\sqrt{1-s^{2}-2v+2sv}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $u\equiv\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}},\hspace{0.5cm}v\equiv\frac{1}{2}\left(q_{1}+q_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 and we used the constraint from the unitarity in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:separation constraint"

\end_inset

) to replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}s'=s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

