\begin_layout Section
Analytical Solution of Interpolation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we solve the interpolation with FRIO in two different ways.
 In the first method, through a parametrization, the problem is converted
 into a minimum error whose solution is well known.
 Then there is one last optimization with respect to a FRIO.
 This method generates the same solution as in Bagan 
\begin_inset Formula $et$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $al$
\end_inset

 in a few lines.
 However to obtain an experimental realization we give an alternative solution
 using Neumark's theorem.
 It is a generalized measurement procedure in which the system is embedded
 in a larger Hilbert space with extra degrees of freedom.
 A unitary transformation entangles the system with the extra degree of
 freedom known as ancilla.
 After this interaction has taken place, projective von Neumann measurements
 are carried out on the ancilla.
 Our input states are qubits, which can be expressed in general as unit
 length vectors in the two dimensional basis spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $|1\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|2\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 In the output of the transformation, we associate the basis state 
\begin_inset Formula $|1\rangle$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $|2\rangle$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle$
\end_inset

 gives no information about the system.
 The unitary transformation should do the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
U|\psi_{1}\rangle_{s}|0\rangle_{a} & =\sqrt{p_{1}}|1\rangle_{s}\ket 1_{a}+\sqrt{r_{1}}|2\rangle_{s}\ket 2_{a}+\sqrt{q_{1}}|0\rangle_{s}\ket 0_{a},\nonumber \\
U|\psi_{2}\rangle_{s}|0\rangle_{a} & =\sqrt{r_{2}}|1\rangle_{s}\ket 1_{a}+\sqrt{p_{2}}|2\rangle_{s}\ket 2_{a}+\sqrt{q_{2}}|0\rangle_{s}\ket 0_{a},\label{eq:frio constraint}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where: 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the probability that state 
\begin_inset Formula $i\thinspace(i=1,2)$
\end_inset

 is correctly identified, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the probability that the detector mistakenly identifies state 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the failure probability, the detector fails to identify the state at
 all.
 A click in the ancilla 
\begin_inset Formula $|0\rangle_{a}$
\end_inset

 means the results are inconclusive and we learn nothing from the measurement.
 From the unitarity conditions we obtain the normalized probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}+r_{i}+q_{i}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We wish to maximize the probability of success, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}=\eta_{1}p_{1}+\eta_{2}p_{2}$
\end_inset

, and minimize the error rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}$
\end_inset

, for a fixed failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}.$
\end_inset

 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}+P_{e}+Q=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inner product of the two equations in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:frio constraint"

\end_inset

) gives the overlap of the input states in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i},\thinspace p_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s=\sqrt{p_{1}r_{2}}+\sqrt{p_{2}r_{1}}+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}},\label{eq:general constraint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s\equiv\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 This is a constraint on the optimization of ME with a FRIO.
 First we show the solution for the case when the input states are prepared
 with equal priors for which the problem is fully solved from the constraint.
 It was initially solved by Chefles and Barnett using a different approach
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chefles1998"

\end_inset

.
 Then we solve the general case for different priors and reproduce the results
 of Bagan 
\begin_inset Formula $et\thinspace al.$
\end_inset

 with two different methods.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equal priors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us first present the solution where the incoming states are given with
 equal a-priori probabilities, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{2}=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies equal error, success and failure rates: 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}=r_{2}$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=p_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=q_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the total error and failure rates reduce to: 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}=r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}=q.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can immediately solve the constraint in Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general constraint"

\end_inset

) by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1-r-Q$
\end_inset

, solving the quadratic equation for the error rate in terms of the failure
 rate and overlap 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, which is also the overall failure rate in the IDP limit for the equal
 priors: 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}\equiv2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}s=s$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
s & = & \sqrt{pr}+\sqrt{pr}+Q,\nonumber \\
Q_{o} & = & 2\sqrt{r(1-r-Q)}+Q,\nonumber \\
(Q_{o}-Q)^{2} & = & 4r(1-r-Q),\nonumber \\
\frac{1}{4}(Q_{o}-Q)^{2} & = & r(1-Q)-r^{2},\nonumber \\
0 & = & r^{2}-(1-Q)r+\frac{1}{4}(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}.\label{eq:quadratic IM}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Solving the quadratic equation and taking the smaller root, 
\begin_inset Formula $i.e$
\end_inset

 the smaller error rate:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r=P_{E}=\frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}],\\
p=P_{S}=\frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)+\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}].
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equal priors case requires no further optimization.
 Simply solving the quadratic equation in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:quadratic IM"

\end_inset

) derived from the constraint the optimal solution is carried out.
 By varying the failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 from zero to 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}$
\end_inset

 we recover the Helstrom and IDP bounds.
 In the Helstrom bound 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Helstrom1969"

\end_inset

 one is not allowed to have inconclusive results, hence setting failure
 rate to zero, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0$
\end_inset

 results in 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\frac{1}{2}[1-\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the IDP limit 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ivanovic1987,Dieks1988,Peres1988"

\end_inset

 where one is not allowed to make an error 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0,$
\end_inset

 while allowing for inconclusive outcomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
0 & = & \frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}],\\
Q & = & Q_{o},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}$
\end_inset

 in the overlap of the input states for equal priors 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}=s.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Arbitrary priors 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because of the recent interest in this problem, we feel it is beneficial
 to show two new and different approaches to its solution.
 The first is more conceptual: a renormalization inspired by E.
 Bagan et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bagan2012"

\end_inset

 allows us to rewrite the problem as a ME problem with an implicit dependence
 on the last free parameter, the failure rate of one state with relation
 to the other.
 This greatly simplifies the problem as the solution to the first part is
 well known and the second is a straight-forward derivative.
 The second solution employs a Lagrange multiplier method that is algebraically
 difficult but useful in its explicit results of individual error rates.
 This in turn is useful in designing an implementation scheme where the
 reflective and transmittance coefficients are expressed in terms of individual
 error and success rate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Transformation of the problem into the Helstrom form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Through a renormalization our problem is converted into the well known Helstrom
 form the solution of which is well known.
 First we define the useful quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\equiv s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}$
\end_inset

 which will serve as normalized overlap and the unitarity constraint from
 Eq.(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general constraint"

\end_inset

) reduces to: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\omega=\sqrt{p_{1}r_{2}}+\sqrt{p_{2}r_{1}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next we renormalize all probabilities in the problem: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \tilde{p}_{i}=\frac{p_{i}}{\alpha_{i}},\nonumber \\
 & \tilde{r_{i}}=\frac{r_{i}}{\alpha_{i}},\nonumber \\
 & \tilde{\omega}=\frac{\omega}{\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}},\\
\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}=1-q_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Now the probabilities are normalized 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{r}_{i}+\tilde{p}_{i}=1$
\end_inset

, and the new normalized overlap is in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{r_{i}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{p}_{i},$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\omega}=\sqrt{\tilde{p}_{1}\tilde{r}_{2}}+\sqrt{\tilde{p_{2}}\tilde{r}_{1}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the above transformation of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 the error rate can be expressed as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{P}_{E}=\tilde{\eta}_{1}\tilde{r}_{1}+\tilde{\eta}_{2}\tilde{r}_{2},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{P}_{E}=\frac{P_{E}}{\eta_{1}\alpha_{1}+\eta_{2}\alpha_{2}}=\frac{P_{E}}{1-Q},\tilde{\eta}_{i}=\frac{\eta_{i}\alpha_{i}}{\eta_{1}\alpha_{1}+\eta_{2}\alpha_{2}}=\frac{\eta_{i}\alpha_{i}}{1-Q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\eta}_{1}+\tilde{\eta}_{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have transformed the problem into a discrimination between two pure states
 with overlap 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\omega}$
\end_inset

 and no explicit failure rate.
 Hence we can simply write down the expression for the minimum error solution
 of two pure states (the Helstrom bound), and then replace the normalized
 quantities with the original expressions: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\tilde{P}_{E} & =\frac{1}{2}[1-\sqrt{1-4\tilde{\eta}_{1}\tilde{\eta}_{2}\tilde{\omega}^{2}}],\nonumber \\
P_{E} & =\frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}}].\label{eq:optimize P_e}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is now one last optimization.
 Given a fixed rate of the average of inconclusive outcomes, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q,$
\end_inset

 what are the individual failure rates 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}.$
\end_inset

 To minimize Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:optimize P_e"

\end_inset

) we maximize the square root term 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}},$
\end_inset

 which in turn means to minimize 
\begin_inset Formula $(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}=(s^{2}+q_{1}q_{2}-2s\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}).$
\end_inset

 The overlap term 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2}$
\end_inset

 is fixed and we are left with 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}q_{2}-2s\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}.}$
\end_inset

 Only one of the 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}'s$
\end_inset

 is an independent variable as we fix the overall failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2},$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Theta & = & q_{1}q_{2}-2s\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}.}\\
\Theta & = & \frac{q_{1}(Q_{0}-\eta_{1}q_{1}^{2})}{\eta_{2}}-2s\sqrt{\frac{q_{1}(Q_{0}-\eta_{1}q_{1}^{2})}{\eta_{2}}}\\
\Theta & = & \frac{\eta_{1}q_{1}Q_{0}-\eta_{1}^{2}q_{1}^{2}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}-2s\sqrt{\frac{\eta_{1}q_{1}Q_{0}-\eta_{1}^{2}q_{1}^{2}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}}\\
\Theta & = & \frac{\tilde{q}_{1}Q_{0}-\tilde{q}_{1}^{2}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}-2s\sqrt{\frac{\tilde{q}_{1}Q_{0}-\tilde{q}_{1}^{2})}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}q_{1}=\tilde{q}.$
\end_inset

 Let's optimize with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{q}_{1}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=\frac{\partial\Theta}{\partial\tilde{q}_{1}}=\frac{Q_{0}-2\tilde{q}_{1}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}-2s\sqrt{\frac{Q_{0}-2\tilde{q}_{1}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
this leads to the optimality condition 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}=2\tilde{q}_{1}=2\eta_{1}q_{1}=2\eta_{2}q_{2},$
\end_inset

 giving the minimal error rate in discriminating two pure states with a
 fixed rate of failure as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\frac{1}{2}[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}].\label{eq:frio}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}=2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}s$
\end_inset

 is the failure rate in the optimal unambiguous state discrimination, which
 our expression reaches when we set 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=0$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand when the failure rate is zero we can recover the Helstrom
 bound for two pure states 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=\frac{1}{2}[1-\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}s^{2}}].$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Lagrange Multipliers Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the above method gives a closed form solution of the average error
 rate in terms of a FRIO it does not produce individual error or success
 rates, i.e the error rates of mistaking state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 for state 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{j}\rangle$
\end_inset

 , which are needed for the implementation in calculating the transmittance
 and reflection coefficients of the beam splitters.
 To obtain these expressions we show another solution to the interpolation
 using the Lagrange multipliers method with the constraint in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general constraint"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to minimize the average error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}$
\end_inset

 subject to the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\sqrt{(1-r_{1}-q_{1})r_{2}}+\sqrt{(1-r_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}}+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}},$
\end_inset

 setting up the function with one Lagrange multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda:$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}+\lambda(s-\sqrt{(1-r_{1}-q_{1})r_{2}}-\sqrt{(1-r_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}}-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Setting the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $dF_{(r_{1},r_{2},\lambda)}/dr_{i}$
\end_inset

 to zero then solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}(\lambda)$
\end_inset

, we exploit the symmetry in the resulting equations to solve for the individual
 error rates 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 as a function of the failure rates 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Subsequent substitution into the constraint gives us the optimal value
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can obtain the total minimum error by replacing the expressions
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}$
\end_inset

 and minimizing 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}$
\end_inset

 under the additional constraint that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}=Q$
\end_inset

.
 This gives us the optimal relationship between failure rates as 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}q_{1}=\eta_{2}q_{2}$
\end_inset

 and the total optimal error rate as 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=2\eta_{1}q_{1}=2\eta_{2}q_{2}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $dF/dr_{1}=0$
\end_inset

 and re-arranging we get: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(2\eta_{1}/\lambda)\sqrt{(1-q_{1}-r_{1})r_{1}}=\sqrt{(1-q_{2}-r_{2})(1-q_{1}-r_{1})}-\sqrt{r_{1}r_{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $dF/dr_{2}=0$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(2\eta_{2}/\lambda)\sqrt{(1-q_{2}-r_{2})r_{2}}=\sqrt{(1-q_{2}-r_{2})(1-q_{1}-r_{1})}-\sqrt{r_{1}r_{2}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This step is algebraically challenging and requires the insight that the
 resulting equations can each be separated into two expressions, left hand
 side depending on only 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 and the right hand sides are equivalent.
 Because both equations have the same multivariable expression, we can set
 the left hand sides equal to a constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $C,$
\end_inset

 which is yet to be determined.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(2\eta_{1}/\lambda)\sqrt{(1-q_{1}-r_{1})r_{1}}=(2\eta_{2}/\lambda)\sqrt{(1-q_{2}-r_{2})r_{2}}\equiv C.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This greatly simplifies the problem, turning it into a quadratic equation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(2\eta_{i}/\lambda)\sqrt{(1-q_{i}-r_{i})r_{i}}=C.\label{eq:C}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}\equiv1-q_{i}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sqrt{(\alpha_{1}-r_{i})r_{i}} & = & (\lambda C)/(2\eta_{i}),\\
r_{i}^{2}-\alpha_{i}r_{i}+\lambda^{2}C^{2}/4\eta_{i}^{2} & = & 0,\\
r_{i}(\pm) & = & 1/2\left(\alpha_{i}\pm\sqrt{\alpha_{i}^{2}-\frac{\lambda^{2}C^{2}}{\eta_{i}^{2}}}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the error rate which we want to be minimized, thus we take the smaller
 root 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}(-).$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r_{1} & = & 1/2\left(\alpha_{1}-\sqrt{\alpha_{1}^{2}-\frac{\delta}{\eta_{1}^{2}}}\right)=1/2\left(\alpha_{1}-A_{1}\right),\label{eq:r1(lambda)}\\
r_{2} & = & 1/2\left(\alpha_{2}-\sqrt{\alpha_{2}^{2}-\frac{\delta}{\eta_{2}^{2}}}\right)=1/2\left(\alpha_{2}-A_{2}\right),\label{eq:r2(lambda)}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\equiv\lambda^{2}C^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}\equiv\sqrt{\alpha_{i}^{2}-(\frac{\lambda^{2}C^{2}}{\eta_{i}^{2}})}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Insert the expression of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r1(lambda)"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r2(lambda)"

\end_inset

) into the constraint from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general constraint"

\end_inset

).
 First let us rewrite the constraint so it simplifies the algebra later:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega=(1-r_{1}-q_{1})r_{2}+(1-r_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}+\sqrt{(1-r_{1}-q_{1})(1-r_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}r_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\equiv(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We use the definition in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:C"

\end_inset

) to reduce the square root term
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{(1-r_{1}-q_{1})(1-r_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}r_{2}}=\frac{\lambda^{2}C^{2}}{4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}},$
\end_inset

 giving
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}=(1-r_{1}-q_{1})r_{2}+(1-r_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}+\frac{\lambda^{2}C^{2}}{4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

Using 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}=1-q_{i},$
\end_inset

 the above expression becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\omega & = & (\alpha_{1}-q_{1})r_{2}+(\alpha_{2}-q_{2})r_{1}+\frac{\delta}{4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}\\
 & = & \alpha_{1}r_{2}-\alpha_{2}r_{1}-2r_{1}r_{2}+\frac{\delta}{4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}\\
 & = & \frac{\alpha_{1}}{2}\left(\alpha_{2}-A_{2}\right)+\frac{\alpha_{2}}{2}\left(\alpha_{1}-A_{1}\right)-\frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha_{1}-A_{1}\right)\left(\alpha_{2}-A_{2}\right)+\frac{\delta}{4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}\\
 & = & \alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}-A_{1}A_{2}+\frac{\delta}{4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 by their respective value
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\omega & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}-\sqrt{\alpha_{1}^{2}-\frac{\delta}{\eta_{1}^{2}}}\sqrt{\alpha_{2}^{2}-\frac{\delta}{\eta_{2}^{2}}}+\delta/\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\right],\\
\sqrt{\alpha_{1}^{2}-\frac{\delta}{\eta_{1}^{2}}}\sqrt{\alpha_{2}^{2}-\frac{\delta}{\eta_{2}^{2}}} & = & \alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}+\delta/\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-2\omega.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Squaring both sides, using 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\alpha_{1}}{\eta_{2}}+\frac{\alpha_{2}}{\eta_{1}}=\frac{\alpha_{1}\eta_{1}+\alpha_{2}\eta_{2}}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}=\frac{\eta_{1}(1-q_{1})+\eta_{2}(1-q_{2})}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}=\frac{1-Q}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}$
\end_inset

 and after some trivial algebra we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\delta\left[\frac{4\omega}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}-\left(\frac{\alpha_{1}}{\eta_{2}}+\frac{\alpha_{2}}{\eta_{1}}\right)\right] & = & 4\omega^{2}-4\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2},\nonumber \\
\delta\left[\frac{4\omega}{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}-\frac{(1-Q)^{2}}{\eta_{1}^{2}\eta_{2}^{2}}\right] & = & 4\omega^{2}-4\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2},\nonumber \\
\delta & = & \frac{\left(\omega^{2}-\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}\right)4\eta_{1}^{2}\eta_{2}^{2}}{4\omega\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-(1-Q)^{2}},
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Now substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r1(lambda)"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r_{1} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha_{1}-\sqrt{\alpha_{1}^{2}-\frac{\lambda^{2}C^{2}}{\eta_{1}^{2}}}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha_{1}-\sqrt{\alpha_{1}^{2}-\frac{1}{\eta_{1}^{2}}\frac{(\omega^{2}-\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2})4\eta_{1}^{2}\eta_{2}^{2}}{4\omega\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-(1-Q)^{2}}}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha_{1}-\sqrt{\frac{\alpha_{1}^{2}[4\omega\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-(1-Q)^{2}]-4\eta[\omega^{2}-\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}]}{4\omega\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-(1-Q)^{2}}}\right).
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The numerator can be greatly simplified:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}^{2}[4\omega\eta_{1}\eta_{2}-(1-Q)^{2}]-4\eta_{2}^{2}[\omega^{2}-\omega\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}]=-\alpha_{1}^{2}(1-Q)^{2}-4\eta_{2}^{2}\omega^{2}+4\omega\eta_{2}\alpha_{1}[\eta_{1}\alpha_{1}+\eta_{2}\alpha_{2}]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $=-[\alpha_{1}(1-Q)-2\eta_{2}\omega]^{2}=-[(1-q_{1})(1-Q)-2\eta_{2}(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}})^{2}]^{2}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The calculation for 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 goes along the same line.
 Expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 become:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r_{1} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[\left(1-q_{1}\right)-\frac{\left(1-q_{1}\right)\left(1-Q\right)-2\eta_{2}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}}{\sqrt{(\left(1-Q\right))^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}}}\right],\\
r_{2} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[\left(1-q_{2}\right)-\frac{\left(1-q_{2}\right)\left(1-Q\right)-2\eta_{1}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}}{\sqrt{\left(1-Q\right)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}}}\right].
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Finally 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 can be substituted into the overall average error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}=\eta_{1}r_{1}+\eta_{2}r_{2}:$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{E} & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[1-\left(\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}\right)-\frac{\left(1-Q\right)\left(\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}\right)-\left(\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}\right)-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}}{\sqrt{\left(1-Q\right)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}}}\right]\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[(1-Q)-\frac{\left(1-Q\right)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}}{\sqrt{\left(1-Q\right)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}}}\right]\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[(1-Q)-\sqrt{\left(1-Q\right)^{2}-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\left(s-\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}\right)^{2}}\right]\label{eq:P_E(q1,q2)}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It has been showed in previous sections that (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:P_E(q1,q2)"

\end_inset

) is optimized for a fixed value of failure rate when 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}q_{1}=\eta_{2}q_{2}.$
\end_inset

 Eq (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:P_E(q1,q2)"

\end_inset

) then reduces to the now well know FRIO form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{E}=\frac{1}{2}\left[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{0})^{2}}\right].
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The individual error and success rates can now be expressed explicitly in
 terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}$
\end_inset

 and most importantly the fixed failure rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{i} & =\frac{1}{2}\left[\left(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}}\right)-\frac{\left(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}}\right)\left(1-Q\right)-\frac{1}{2\eta_{i}}(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}}\right],\label{eq:r_i}\\
p_{i} & =\frac{1}{2}\left[\left(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}}\right)+\frac{\left(1-\frac{Q}{2\eta_{i}}\right)\left(1-Q\right)-\frac{1}{2\eta_{i}}(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q-Q_{o})^{2}}}\right].\label{eq:p_i}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the first time that the individual error and failure rates have
 been calculated.
 An immediate application is that it can now be used in the calculations
 of the coefficients beam splitters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Choosing the physical implementation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main reason to seek a solution using the Neumark setup is because it
 lends itself to an optical implementation.
 This implementation, as we will see, can be carried out using only linear
 optical elements (beam splitters and a mirror).
 The possible states are represented by single photons and a photodetector
 will carry out the measurement process at the output.
 To choose the basis we start with the two mode vacuum state 
\begin_inset Formula $|00\rangle.$
\end_inset

 The total number of photons in both modes is one.
 This two dimensional Hilbert space where our photons live can be spanned
 by the states 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|10\rangle,|01\rangle\}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $|10\rangle=a_{1}^{\dagger}|00\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|01\rangle=a_{2}^{\dagger}|00\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 are creation operators corresponding to two different modes of the electromagne
tic field.
 The basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|10\rangle,|01\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the basis of qubit in 
\begin_inset Formula $\{|0\rangle,|1\rangle\}.$
\end_inset

 The most general input state can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}\rangle=\alpha_{i}|0\rangle+\beta_{i}|1\rangle=\alpha_{i}|10\rangle+\beta_{i}|01\rangle$
\end_inset

 which can be produced by sending a photon into a beam splitter with some
 transmission and reflection coefficient, where the modes 1 and 2 correspond
 to the output modes of the beam splitter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A general 
\begin_inset Formula $2N$
\end_inset

 port is a linear device with 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 input and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 output ports.
 It can be constructed from beam splitters and mirrors 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bergou2009"

\end_inset

.
 For our work we will need a six-port, three input ports and three output
 ports.
 Let us denote the annihilation operators corresponding to the input modes
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j\text{\thinspace in }},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,2,3$
\end_inset

 then the output operators are given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{j\text{\thinspace out }}=U^{-1}a_{i\text{\thinspace in }}U=\sum M_{jk}a_{k\text{\thinspace in }},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{jk}$
\end_inset

 are the elements of the 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times N$
\end_inset

 unitary matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M.$
\end_inset

 In the Schrodinger picture, the 
\begin_inset Formula $in$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $out$
\end_inset

 states are related by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{\psi}_{out}=U\ket{\psi}_{in}.
\]

\end_inset

 In general an 
\begin_inset Formula $in$
\end_inset

 state that contains a single photon can be described by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{\psi}_{in}=\sum_{j=1}^{3}c_{j}a_{j}^{\dagger}\ket{000},
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j=1}^{3}\left|c_{j}\right|=1.$
\end_inset

 The output state is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\ket{\psi}_{in} & = & U\sum_{j=1}^{3}c_{j}a_{j}^{\dagger}U^{-1}\ket{000}\\
 & = & \sum_{j,k=1}^{3}c_{j}M_{jk}^{T}a_{j}^{\dagger}\ket{000},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where we have made use of the fact that the vacuum is invariant under the
 transformation, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 To simplify the notation in the implementation section let:
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{100}\equiv\ket 1,\thinspace\ket{010}\equiv\ket 2,\thinspace\ket{001}\equiv\ket 3.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Implementation: equal priors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will first show the implementation of FRIO for equal priors.
 The Neumark in direct sum notation setup will be used to calculate the
 unitary matrix.
 The two input states to be discriminated can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle_{in}=|1\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle_{in}=\cos\theta|1\rangle+\sin\theta|2\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U|1\rangle & = & \sqrt{p}|1\rangle+\sqrt{r}|2\rangle+\sqrt{q}|3\rangle,\label{eq:eq1}\\
U(\cos\theta|1\rangle+\sin\theta|2\rangle) & = & \sqrt{r}|1\rangle+\sqrt{p}|2\rangle+\sqrt{q}|3\rangle,\label{eq:eq2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the error and success rate was calculated in section 4.1.1: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[(1-Q)-\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}\right],\label{eq:r}\\
p & = & \frac{1}{2}\left[(1-Q)+\sqrt{(1-Q)^{2}-(Q_{o}-Q)^{2}}\right],\label{eq:p}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the Neumark setup we can read out six out of nine elements of the unitary
 matrix.
 Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eq1"

\end_inset

) gives the first column, Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eq2"

\end_inset

) gives the second column and the last column can be constructed from the
 conditions of unitarity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get first column, multiply Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eq1"

\end_inset

) from the left with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra 1,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra 2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra 3:$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle1|U|1\rangle=U_{11}=\sqrt{p},
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle2|U|1\rangle=U_{21}=\sqrt{q},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle3|U|1\rangle=U_{31}=\sqrt{r}.
\]

\end_inset

To get the second column, multiply 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eq2"

\end_inset

 from the left with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra 1,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra 2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra 3:$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cos\theta\langle1|U|1\rangle+\sin\theta\langle1|U|2\rangle=\cos\theta U_{11}+\sin\theta U_{12}=\sqrt{r},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cos\theta\langle2|U|1\rangle+\sin\theta\langle2|U|2\rangle=\cos\theta U_{21}+\sin\theta U_{22}=\sqrt{p},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cos\theta\langle3|U|1\rangle+\sin\theta\langle3|U|2\rangle=\cos\theta U_{31}+\sin\theta U_{32}=\sqrt{q}.
\]

\end_inset

 Using the solution of the first column 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i1}$
\end_inset

, gives the entries to second column 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i2}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3),$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\sqrt{p}_{1}+\sin\theta U_{12}=\sqrt{r_{2}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{12}=\frac{\sqrt{r}-\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\sqrt{q_{1}}+\sin\theta U_{22}=\sqrt{p_{2}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{22}=\frac{[\sqrt{p}-\sqrt{r}Q_{o}]}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\sqrt{r_{1}}+\sin\theta U_{32}=\sqrt{q_{2}}\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{32}=\sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{1+Q_{o}}}$
\end_inset

 ,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta=Q_{o}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\theta=\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The remaining elements be calculated from the conditions of the unitarity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{T}U=I$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i1}^{2}+U_{i2}^{2}+U_{i3}^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{13}=\pm\sqrt{1-U_{11}^{2}-U_{12}^{2}}=\pm\sqrt{1-p-\frac{r+pQ_{o}^{2}-2\sqrt{pr}Q_{0}}{1-Q_{0}^{2}}}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{Q-Q_{o}^{2}+2\sqrt{pr}Q_{0}}{1-Q_{0}^{2}}}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{Q}{1-Q_{0}}}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{pr}=\frac{1}{2}(Q_{o}-Q)$
\end_inset

 was used, which is derived from the multiplication of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:p"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{23}=\pm\sqrt{1-U_{21}^{2}-U_{22}^{2}}=\pm\sqrt{1-r-\frac{p+rQ_{o}^{2}-2\sqrt{pr}Q_{0}}{1-Q_{0}^{2}}}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{Q}{1-Q_{0}}}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{33}=\pm\sqrt{1-U_{31}^{2}-U_{32}^{2}}=\pm\sqrt{1-Q-\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{1+Q_{o}}}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{1+Q_{o}-2Q}{1+Q_{o}}}=\pm\frac{\sqrt{p}+\sqrt{r}}{\sqrt{1+Q_{o}}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to notice the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{(1+Q_{o}-2Q)}=\sqrt{p}+\sqrt{r}$
\end_inset

 which is somewhat unexpected.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The full unitary, with the signs of the last column elements chosen so that
 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{13}^{2}+U_{23}^{2}+U_{33}^{2}=1,$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p} & \frac{\sqrt{r}-\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & -\sqrt{\frac{Q}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{r} & \frac{\sqrt{p}-\sqrt{r}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & -\sqrt{\frac{Q}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{Q} & \sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{1+Q_{o}}} & \frac{\sqrt{p}+\sqrt{r}}{\sqrt{1+Q_{o}}}
\end{pmatrix}.\label{eq:U(equal prior)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In this representation the above matrix can be shown that it satisfies all
 the unitary conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The unitary in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:U(equal prior)"

\end_inset

) interpolates between the optimal ME and UD schemes varying the fixed rate
 of inconclusive results 
\begin_inset Formula $Q.$
\end_inset

 Setting the failure rate to zero, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0,$
\end_inset

 collapses it into the unitary of optimal ME:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{ME}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p} & \frac{\sqrt{r}-\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & 0\\
\sqrt{r} & \frac{\sqrt{p}-\sqrt{r}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
which can be simplified further by noticing 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{12})^{2}=\left(\frac{\sqrt{r}-\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}}\right)^{2}=r,$
\end_inset

 similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{22})^{2}=\left(\frac{\sqrt{p}-\sqrt{r}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}}\right)^{2}=p$
\end_inset

, simplifying the unitary into: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{ME}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p} & \sqrt{r} & 0\\
\sqrt{r} & -\sqrt{p} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset

only one beam splitter in needed for optimal ME measurements.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand setting the error rate of the unitary 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:U(equal prior)"

\end_inset

 to zero gives the optimal UD unitary,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{UD}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p} & -\frac{\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & -\sqrt{\frac{Q_{0}}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
0 & \frac{\sqrt{p}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & -\sqrt{\frac{Q_{o}}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{Q_{0}} & \sqrt{\frac{Q_{o}(1-Q_{o})}{1+Q_{o}}} & \sqrt{\frac{1-Q_{o}}{1+Q_{o}}}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All three beamsplitters are still necessary for a general UD measurement.
 This is because the measurement is essentially two-step: in the first step
 the states are made orthogonal, then upon succeeding a projective measurement
 is performed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now express the interpolating unitary in terms of three beamsplitters,
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $U=M_{1}M_{2}M_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 This ordering was derived using the Reck-Zeilinger algorithm which says
 that any discreet finite unitary matrix can be expressed in terms of beamsplitt
ers and phase shifters.
 The beamsplitters can be written in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 and it is easy to check the unitarity condition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin^{2}\omega_{i}+\cos^{2}\omega_{i}=1.$
\end_inset

 Then the task is that of calculating 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{1}=\begin{pmatrix}\sin\omega & \cos\omega_{1} & 0\\
\cos\omega & -\sin\omega & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{2}=\begin{pmatrix}\sin\omega_{2} & 0 & \cos\omega_{2}\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
\cos\omega_{2} & 0 & -\sin\omega_{2}
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{3}=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \sin\omega_{3} & \cos\omega_{3}\\
0 & \cos\omega_{3} & -\sin\omega_{3}
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=M_{1}M_{2}M_{3}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{p} & \frac{\sqrt{r}-\sqrt{p}Q_{o}}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & \sqrt{\frac{Q}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{r} & \frac{[\sqrt{p}-\sqrt{r}Q_{o}]}{\sqrt{1-Q_{o}^{2}}} & \sqrt{\frac{Q}{1+Q_{o}}}\\
\sqrt{Q} & \sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{1+Q_{o}}} & \sqrt{\frac{1+Q_{o}-2Q}{1+Q_{o}}}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\begin{pmatrix}\sin\omega_{1}\sin\omega_{2} & \cos\omega_{1}\sin\omega_{3}+\sin\omega_{1}\cos\omega_{2}\cos\omega_{3} & \cos\omega_{1}\cos\omega_{3}-\sin\omega_{1}\cos\omega_{2}\sin\omega_{3}\\
\cos\omega_{1}\sin\omega_{2} & -\sin\omega_{1}\sin\omega_{3}+\cos\omega_{1}\cos\omega_{2}\cos\omega_{3} & -\sin\omega_{1}\cos\omega_{3}-\cos\omega_{1}\cos\omega_{2}\sin\omega_{3}\\
\cos\omega_{2} & -\sin\omega_{2}\cos\omega_{3} & \sin\omega_{2}\sin\omega_{3}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives nine equations and only three independent variables to be calculated.
 All the elements can be obtained by using just 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{31},U_{32},U_{21}:$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{2}=U_{31}=\sqrt{Q},\sin\omega_{2}=\sqrt{1-r^{2}}=\sqrt{1-Q}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{3}=-\sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{(1+Q_{o})(1-Q)}},\sin\omega_{3}=\sqrt{\frac{1+Q_{o}-2Q}{(1-Q)(1+Q_{o})}}=\frac{\sqrt{p}+\sqrt{r}}{\sqrt{(1-Q)(1+Q_{o})}}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\omega_{1}=\sqrt{\frac{r}{1-Q}},\sin\omega_{1}=\sqrt{\frac{p}{1-Q}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The three beamsplitters with the proper coefficients of reflectivity and
 transmittance are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{1}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{\frac{p}{1-Q}} & \sqrt{\frac{r}{1-Q}} & 0\\
\sqrt{\frac{r}{1-Q}} & -\sqrt{\frac{p}{1-Q}} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{2}=\begin{pmatrix}\sqrt{1-Q} & 0 & \sqrt{Q}\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
\sqrt{Q} & 0 & -\sqrt{1-Q}
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{3}=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \sqrt{\frac{1+Q_{o}-2Q}{(1-Q)(1+Q_{o})}} & -\sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{(1+Q_{o})(1-Q)}}\\
0 & -\sqrt{\frac{Q(1-Q_{o})}{(1+Q_{o})(1-Q)}} & -\sqrt{\frac{1+Q_{o}-2Q}{(1-Q)(1+Q_{o})}}
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By choosing the FRIO this matrix minimizes the error rate and maximizes
 the rate of success.
 Hence, by setting the FRIO to zero we obtain the setup to the minimum error
 problem.
 On the other hand, setting the error rate to zero gives the setup of the
 optimal unambiguous discrimination where the optimal inconclusive rate
 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{o}=s$
\end_inset

.
 This simplifies the works of the experimentalists because now they only
 need one setup and are not restrained to the extreme points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Implementation: Unequal priors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we derive the beamsplitter coefficients necessary to interpolate
 minimum error measurements with a 
\begin_inset Formula $FRIO$
\end_inset

 when the input states are prepared with different a priori probabilities.
 The two input states to be discriminated are 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle_{in}=|1\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle_{in}=\cos\theta|1\rangle+\sin\theta|2\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 A unitary operator carries out the operation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
U|1\rangle & =\sqrt{p_{1}}|1\rangle+\sqrt{r_{1}}|2\rangle+\sqrt{q_{1}}|3\rangle,\label{eq:U1}\\
U(\cos\theta|1\rangle+\sin\theta|2\rangle) & =\sqrt{r_{2}}|1\rangle+\sqrt{p_{2}}|2\rangle+\sqrt{q_{2}}|3\rangle.\label{eq:U2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


