\begin_layout Chapter*
Appendix 2: Lagrange Multipliers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our works we have relied quite heavily on the method of Lagrange multipliers
 when optimizing a function which was under the restriction of a constraint.
 We now show how it works 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Barnett2009"

\end_inset

.
 The method can be applied to a function of any number of variables but
 it can be more clearly explained in two variables.
 Suppose that we need to find the stationary points of a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y),$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are the two variables, subject to the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x,y)=0.$
\end_inset

 If the constraint is simple then we can solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $y,$
\end_inset

 plug it into the function and solve 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial f/\partial y=0.$
\end_inset

 However for a more complicated constraint this can easily lead to a very
 high order equation with cannot be solved analytically.
 In the case of exact cloning, doing just so leads to a sixth order equation
 which is of little use.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To find the stationary points of a function of two variables such as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y),$
\end_inset

 we could just take the total differential 
\begin_inset Formula $df$
\end_inset

 and set it to zero
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
df=\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}dx+\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}dy=0,\label{eq:lagrange 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which leads to two conditions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}=0,\ \ \frac{\partial f}{\partial y}=0.\label{eq:lagrange 0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However there is a constraint which means that the differentials 
\begin_inset Formula $dx$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $dy$
\end_inset

 are not independent, they are related to the total differential of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dg=\frac{\partial g}{\partial x}dx+\frac{\partial g}{\partial y}dy=0.\label{eq:lagrange 2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiplying (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange 2"

\end_inset

) by the Lagrange parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and adding it to (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange 1"

\end_inset

) we get 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d(f+\lambda g)=(\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}+\lambda\frac{\partial g}{\partial x})dx+(\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}+\lambda\frac{\partial g}{\partial y})dy
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation can be satisfied by choosing the Lagrange multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 such that the following two conditions are satisfied:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}+\lambda\frac{\partial g}{\partial x}=0\label{eq:lagrange x}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}+\lambda\frac{\partial g}{\partial y}=0\label{eq:lagrange y}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get the stationary points of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)$
\end_inset

 follow this procedure:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Solve the two equations: (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange x"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange y"

\end_inset

) in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y(\lambda)$
\end_inset

; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Plug 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 into the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x,y)$
\end_inset

 ;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Plug the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y(\lambda)$
\end_inset

; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Plug 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 into the function which was to be optimized 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we have seen how the Lagrange multipliers method works, we can
 simplify the procedure by optimizing the function following function:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F(x,y)=f(x,y)+\lambda g(x,y)\label{eq:lagrange full}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with respect to the the independent variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y.$
\end_inset

 Differentiating (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange full"

\end_inset

) with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y,$
\end_inset

 we obtain equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange x"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lagrange y"

\end_inset

).
 The rest of the procedure is the same.
 This is the exact procedure we used for our works, for example in optimizing
 the error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}(r_{1},r_{2})$
\end_inset

 with one constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $s(r_{1},r_{2}).$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

